commentText: Those wages will level out. We're early in the plan to bring back jobs to America. The problem is that we're trying to compete on a playing field that is not level. The theory that supports this is that Americans were supposed to keep the well paying jobs while the lower paying jobs were sent to countries that have lower wages. In theory, this is a win-win (pareto efficiency) in that the lower wage countries get jobs that increase their standard of living and produce goods at a lower cost for the other country. What is missed in this equation is that grass roots industry, most times a manufacturing/value-add types of industry, are the basis of more complex economies. It is a multiplier effect with a high number of instances of a low multiplier. All these instances combined leads to a large impact. Add to this that the technology that is the basis of the economic advantage that produces the high paying jobs does not stay unique for long periods, and you have those jobs too becoming portable. Why have a manufacturing team on one side of the globe, creating material communication and responsiveness issues with the engineering team on the other side of the globe? Move the engineering to the same location as manufacturing and you have a more responsive company.   That said, we are in the process of leveling that playing field with economic tooling. The jobs are starting to come back and we will start to see the multiplier effect and labour supply/demand fill in the missing middle class. It is a very interesting time to be alive! We are witnessing the reversal of decades of bad policy.   The only part we don't fully see yet is how this will shake out in a stock market that makes it's money on growth. I think the time of free money is coming to a close, along with the close of abusive economic policy.

commentText: Unions deserve to die... the bureaucracy sucks the income of the actual worker to pay a select few people to do nothing thus discouraging the whole. They are therefore as bad as the companies they sought to oppose. Who can we organize to oppose the oligarchical bureaucracy of the unions themselves?    I do oppose non-compete agreements, anything that is anticompetitive is generally going to impoverish most and enrich a smaller subset. However, if a company is going to train someone, it does make sense to have a limited duration non-compete (not one that is after you leave, but one that is from the start date). We need to encourage companies to train their employees: schools are too expensive now and need some competition to the job training world.    Automation certainly can pose a problem but there is so much opportunity in other areas but people can't quickly (if at all in certain situations) re-tool so that is a genuine problem.   But the other issue you didn't cover is government regulation: it stifles competition and limits business growth/startups. Government restrictions typically benefit the larger company since they can more easily comply. Since small business owners make up the lion's share of the employers, we need to figure out how to encourage this demographic.

commentText: Prepping. There are different levels in how to prep. One layer all need to consider is prepping with or without electricity. No electricity then you have no working toilets, no heat or air conditioning, no refrigeration and perhaps no gas from gas stations etc. Do you know hoe to make your own toilette? Dispose of waste? Do have material or backup heating sources like propane single stove to make heat or a fire? Do you have caste iron skillet or a cowboy coffee pot? Do you know how to disinfect water? Do you know how to make your own wine, beer or spirits? Good bartering material. Anyway, there is a book called One Second After by William Forstchen with a forward by Newt Gingrich. It's about a family and their community during a grid outage that lasts over a year. It's about how people change between family members, friends and community when it becomes everyone for themselves once the supplies disappear. I highly recommend reading it. Even if you don't prep herein for life without a grid, you are at least aware of what may be so you know what to expect and how to react if it happens. It is a book that was recommended on the house floor of Congress , Homeland Security and by the military.

videoTitle: Robots, automation bringing more jobs, productivity to US economy?
videoDescription: ROBO Global CIO Bill Studebaker on the impact of robots and increased automation on the job market.
commentText: Let's look at one part of his argument. It is true that Amazon is hiring thousands of employees to pick the orders in their warehouses as more people place orders online. It is also true that those warehouses are highly automated with the robots picking up the shelves and taking them to the human picker to package for the customers.  The issue that's not being addressed is that Amazon holds a yearly contest where people design robots to replace those workers. So far those robots have been found wanting in this department, but, as with all technology, as more and more companies and startups look to grab this golden ring and become the supplier to Amazon, it is only a matter of time before a company solves this particular problem due to the competition and speed with which technology moves. In other words, those jobs are, at best, temporary. (In fact, I read an article just the other day that states that a company has already solved this problem. Whether or not that is true remains to be seen.)  One of the largest costs to businesses are labor. Automation is specifically designed to lower this cost. If I'm an employer, why would I want to keep the same amount of employees on my payroll if I can substitute them for automation which can be depreciated over time, replaced at a specific cost, and sold for scrap at the end of its life? Automation doesn't call in sick, doesn't need vacations, and can work as many hours and you want without extra pay. There is very few downsides to replacing the worker from the employers point of view.

videoTitle: How is wage growth measured and what does it tell us about the economy?
videoDescription: Yahoo Finance's Brian Cheung breaks explains why measuring wage growth is a key indicator when evaluating the economy.
commentText: This is probably because all the new jobs are temporary, gig, or contract jobs with no benefits. The inflation indicator used by the Fed takes into account job benefits like insurance that will fall moreso on the employer due to hyperinflation in healthcare. If all the new jobs don't have benefits, then the cost of medical care falls on the consumer, which is best measured by CPI iirc. The CPI has been showing that wages have either stagnated or failed to keep up with inflation. Furthermore, the wage growth that is being measured is likely predominantly in the upper-class of wealth. We all know the statistic about how much CEO pay has outstripped worker pay over the years, so it's probably the case that competition for labour is only occurring in the upper-class. There won't be any increase in demand if the person's buying power remains the same, and a definitely decrease if the cost of living continues to increase while wages stagnate. If the Fed wants inflation, it should figure out a better way to give money to a broader range of consumers, because it isn't really trickling down atm while the cost of living increases.
